{"node_id": "5c5817c8", "title": "Why use messages?", "path": "graph-api > Graph API overview > State > Working with Messages in Graph State > Why use messages?", "content": "Most modern LLM providers have a chat model interface that accepts a list of messages as input. LangChain's [chat model interface](/oss/python/langchain/models) in particular accepts a list of message objects as inputs. These messages come in a variety of forms such as [`HumanMessage`](https://reference.langchain.com/python/langchain/messages/#langchain.messages.HumanMessage) (user input) or [`AIMessage`](https://reference.langchain.com/python/langchain/messages/#langchain.messages.AIMessage) (LLM response).\n\nTo read more about what message objects are, please refer to the [Messages conceptual guide](/oss/python/langchain/messages).", "summary": "Explains the use of messages as input for LLM chat models, referencing LangChain's interface and message types like HumanMessage and AIMessage.", "keywords": ["LLM", "chat model", "messages", "HumanMessage", "AIMessage", "LangChain", "input", "interface", "API"]}